Routing — how packets find their destination.

So your machine has an address. Now, when it wants to send a packet somewhere, say to ninety-three dot one-eighty-four dot two-sixteen dot thirty-four, how does it decide where to actually send it? It consults its routing table, which tells the kernel two things: which interface to send the packet through, and which next hop, which gateway, to hand it to. The routing table is essentially a list of rules of the form "if the destination matches this network, use this gateway via this interface," and the kernel always picks the most specific matching rule.

You view your routes with the command ip route. A typical result has just two lines. The first reads: default, via one-ninety-two dot one-sixty-eight dot one dot one, dev eth0. That's the default gateway: it says, for anything that doesn't match a more specific rule, send it to that address by way of the eth0 interface. On a home network that gateway is your router; in the cloud it's a virtual gateway provided by your VPC. The second line reads something like: one-ninety-two dot one-sixty-eight dot one dot zero slash twenty-four, dev eth0, src one-ninety-two dot one-sixty-eight dot one dot forty-two. That says: for the local network, no gateway is needed at all, because it's directly attached; just use eth0, with this source address.

And that's the shape of most machines' routing: exactly two rules. The local network is reachable directly, and everything else goes via the gateway. More complex setups, like VPNs or servers with several network cards, add more rules on top, but the pattern is the same.

You manipulate routes with ip route add, ip route del, and ip route change, though, like the address changes, these are temporary; for persistence you configure them through NetworkManager. And finally, the single most useful debugging command in this section: ip route get, followed by a destination address. It tells you exactly which interface and gateway will be used to reach that destination. Reach for it whenever you're debugging and asking yourself, "wait, is my traffic actually going where I think it's going?"
